## ✍️ 1. Thought Leadership Blog: The Art of Story Indexing

### That’s what Storytellers do: “You are the story!”

I resonate with the words of Geeta Ramanujam, a well-known storyteller from South India. Each day, in the pursuit to fill my bag of stories, I capture subtle moments of conversations and experiences to etch them in my memory. 

But at that exact minute when a relevant story can be quoted, all that I go through is absolute brain freeze. Though I cherish my stories with fond love, why don’t they help me when in need?

When I approached a veteran storyteller for an answer to this question, this is what I heard...

#### The Experiment
The veteran started by asking four quick questions:
*   Can you tell me a childhood story that tells you not all competencies guarantee success?
*   Another story that says making merry needs to be well-timed.
*   A story on how being too dutiful can be troublesome.
*   A story on believing magical combinations.

Seeing my plight that I could barely answer those questions, the veteran tweaked the same questions and made it easy for me. When asked for a story on:

1. **"Slow and steady wins the race"** ➔ I proudly replied, *“The Hare and the Tortoise.”*
2. **"Putting work before play"** ➔ I knew it was *“The Ant and the Grasshopper.”*
3. **"Not to meddle with others’ jobs"** ➔ My immediate answer was *“The Donkey and the Dog.”*
4. **"Using your brains in the need of the hour"** ➔ The story of *“The Thirsty Crow”* struck me instantly.

#### The Epiphany: It's All About Indexing
What exactly made the difference in the way the two sets of questions were formed? Was it the perspective, the context, or was it the emotion? Well, the more I thought about the questions, the more confused I was.

The veteran explained that it is **not about picking the right story nor about working on your grey cells. It is about indexing right.**

> ### 🍳 The Recipe for Successful Convergence
> Each time you come across a story that is worth sharing, practice the following:
> 
> 1. **Pause & Verbalize:** Pause to think and verbalize the core message from each story that you come across.
> 2. **Deconstruct & Visualize:** Visualize the story as discrete moments to identify a myriad of scenarios and ways to use the same story with a different approach.
> 3. **Internalize & Tag:** Try to make that story a part of your daily conversation. Internalize the story such that it occurs to you naturally. This will help you identify as many mental tags as possible to recollect the story with greater ease.

When I understood that the twist is not about storing a lot of stories but to catalogue them intelligently, I started rewiring my brain. Aren’t you?

